Alcohol. Alcohol and marijuana

01:02:18.020 --> 01:02:20.740
are well known to induce states that are

01:02:20.740 --> 01:02:21.970
pseudo sleep like.

01:02:21.970 --> 01:02:24.300
Especially, when people fall asleep

01:02:24.300 --> 01:02:27.846
after having consumed alcohol or THC,

01:02:27.846 --> 01:02:30.643
one of the active components of marijuana.

01:02:31.670 --> 01:02:33.900
Alcohol, THC

01:02:33.900 --> 01:02:37.213
and most things like them,

01:02:37.213 --> 01:02:41.740
meaning things that
increase serotonin, or GABA

01:02:41.740 --> 01:02:43.760
are going to disrupt the pattern of sleep.

01:02:43.760 --> 01:02:44.950
They're going to disrupt the depth.

01:02:44.950 --> 01:02:46.859
They're going to disrupt

01:02:46.859 --> 01:02:48.280
the overall sequencing
of more slow wave sleep

01:02:48.280 --> 01:02:50.540
early in the night and more
REM sleep later in the night.

01:02:50.540 --> 01:02:52.436
That's just the reality.

01:02:52.436 --> 01:02:55.079
There are some things that

01:02:55.079 --> 01:02:57.570
at least, in a few
studies that I could find

01:02:57.570 --> 01:02:59.580
seem to suggest that you could

01:02:59.580 --> 01:03:01.770
increase the amount of slow wave sleep

01:03:01.770 --> 01:03:04.960
using things like arginine,
the amino acid arginine.

01:03:04.960 --> 01:03:05.850
Although, you really wanna check.

01:03:05.850 --> 01:03:07.970
Arginine can have effects
on heart, et cetera

01:03:07.970 --> 01:03:09.310
has other effects.

01:03:09.310 --> 01:03:11.887
But, alcohol, THC, not
gonna be great for sleep

01:03:11.887 --> 01:03:13.720
and depth of sleep.

01:03:13.720 --> 01:03:15.590
You might feel like you
can fall asleep faster,

01:03:15.590 --> 01:03:17.390
but the sleep that you're accessing

01:03:17.390 --> 01:03:19.550
really isn't the kind of
deep restorative sleep

01:03:19.550 --> 01:03:21.920
that you should be getting.

01:03:21.920 --> 01:03:24.170
Now, of course, if that's what you need

01:03:24.170 --> 01:03:26.390
in order to sleep and that's
within your protocols,

